@Xword Junkie 

Just to add to what XwJ has said: while thinking about multiplying 1 or 0 by themselves seems trivial in the world of scalar algebra (the special case we learn in Jr High and/or High School), the properties of idempotent matrices are extremely useful in the matrix algebra underlying regression analysis of large sets of data.  The Identity matrix (matrix analog of the scalar “1”) and null matrix (matrix analog of “0”) are just special cases of a whole universe of idempotent NxM matrices.  The algebraic properties of these special matrices allow us to construct many important tests (one small example: “hmmm.  Out of the thousands of data entries that my forecast derives from, this small subset seems to be having a large impact on my projection. (If I have any analytical integrity) I’d better double-check this subset to make sure my forecast, or estimated functional relation, isn’t being driven by a few erroneous data entries,”)

So, yeah, the word itself is pretty idiosyncratic if you haven’t studied matrix algebra and/or  (e.g.) its application to statistical regression. But, in the Information Age, when we are constantly peppered with claims based on statistical (e.g.) econometrics and con-ometrics, things like idempotent matrices are not unimportant.

